### 3.2 A Motivating Example

```
String cmd, val; // 0 <= val <= 100
Servo steering, throttle;
while (Serial.available() > 0) {
    cmd = Serial.readStringUntil( \}\);
    val = Serial.readStringUntil('\n');
    if (cmd == "steer")
        steering.write(val.toInt());
    else if (cmd == "motor")
        throttle.write(val.toInt());
}
```

Listing 3: Steering Control from P2IM (simplified)
Most rehosting-based firmware fuzzers assign stateless models to MMIO reads in the firmware under test and never change the assigned models. This may prevent a fuzzer from covering much of the firmware's data-intensive application code since the models poorly describe MMIO reads that collectively retrieve a data chunk. Sec. 3.1 has shown the MMIO models generated by such a fuzzer and ES-Fuzz, respectively, for testing the Steering Control firmware from P2IM. Here, we use these MMIO models and firmware to further illustrate the above limitation of existing models and motivate the use of ES-Fuzz's models in firmware fuzzing.

The Steering Control firmware periodically executes the loop in Listing 3 to parse newly received commands and adjust its servo motors accordingly. It takes the commands character-by-character from a data register (UART RHR) at $0 \times 400 \mathrm{e} 0818$. It expects each command to specify a motor's name and new parameter, separated by a comma. It also expects the name cmd to be "steer" or "motor" and the parameter val to be an integer between 0 and 180 . (val $<0$ and val $>180$ affect the firmware's control flow differently.)

The firmware's expectations imply that different characters (letters, digits, and a comma) in a command follow different syntactic rules. If MMIO reads from the UART RHR are assigned the stateless model in Listing 1, the model cannot distinguish a "letter" read from a "digit" read. In contrast, the stateful model in Listing 2 uniquely characterizes each of the MMIO reads for retrieving a command.

After extracting cmd and val from a command, the firmware writes val to the servo motor indicated by cmd. That is, the same val affects the firmware's control flow differently depending on cmd. If MMIO reads from the UART RHR stick with one model throughout fuzz-testing, the single model must account for all these val semantics. Such a model is either too complex to build in one shot or too generic to use. The model in Listing 1 is the latter case. In contrast, the adaptable model in Listing 2 evolves during fuzztesting to contain more single-valued stateful models and represent richer semantics of a command.

In the above example, we compare the MMIO models of Fuzzware and ES-Fuzz for the firmware's MMIO reads that collectively
retrieve a command. The comparison suggests that there is room for improvement of SOTA MMIO models used in firmware fuzzing. The models cannot properly describe the reads for retrieving a data chunk. This limits the code coverage of firmware fuzzers, for such MMIO reads are common in the application code of ES firmware. To cover more of the application code, the fuzzers should instead assign stateful and adaptable models to such MMIO reads.
